RAG RESEARCH SYSTEM
===================

A lightweight Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) system for querying document
collections through a natural language chat interface. The system combines local
vector embeddings with a cloud-hosted large language model to deliver accurate,
context-grounded answers from your own documents.


OVERVIEW
--------

This system indexes .docx documents into a persistent local vector database and
enables interactive question-answering over the indexed content. Retrieval is
performed semantically using dense vector search; generation is handled by Ollama
Cloud's hosted LLM endpoint.

Architecture:

  .docx files  -->  text extraction  -->  chunking
       |
       v
  ChromaDB (local vector store, persistent)
       |
       v
  semantic search (all-MiniLM-L6-v2, ONNX, runs locally)
       |
       v
  Ollama Cloud LLM (gpt-oss:120b-cloud)
       |
       v
  answer streamed to terminal


STACK
-----

  Component         Technology
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Vector store      ChromaDB  (persistent, local)
  Embeddings        all-MiniLM-L6-v2  (ONNX, local)
  LLM               Ollama Cloud  (gpt-oss:120b-cloud)
  Document parser   python-docx
  Runtime           Python 3.12


REQUIREMENTS
------------

  - Python 3.12  (Python 3.14 is NOT supported — ML packages require 3.12)
  - An Ollama Cloud account and API key  (https://ollama.com/settings/keys)
  - .docx documents to query


SETUP — macOS / Linux
---------------------

1. Clone the repository

     git clone <repository-url>
     cd ragresearch

2. Install Python 3.12 (if not already installed)

     macOS:
       brew install python@3.12

     Linux (Ubuntu/Debian):
       sudo apt install python3.12 python3.12-venv

3. Create a virtual environment

     python3.12 -m venv .venv
     source .venv/bin/activate

4. Install dependencies

     pip install -r requirements.txt

5. Configure your API key

   Create a file named .env in the project root:

     OLLAMA_API_KEY=your_ollama_api_key_here

   Get your key at: https://ollama.com/settings/keys

6. Add documents

   Place your .docx files in a folder (e.g. data/):

     mkdir data
     cp your_documents/*.docx data/

7. Run

     python rag.py data


SETUP — Windows
---------------

1. Install Python 3.12

   Download from: https://www.python.org/downloads/release/python-3128/
   During installation, check "Add python.exe to PATH".

2. Open Command Prompt and navigate to the project folder

     cd path\to\ragresearch

3. Create a virtual environment

     python -m venv .venv
     .venv\Scripts\activate

4. Install dependencies

     pip install -r requirements.txt

5. Configure your API key

   Create a file named .env in the project root:

     OLLAMA_API_KEY=your_ollama_api_key_here

6. Add documents

     mkdir data

   Copy your .docx files into the data\ folder.

7. Run

     python rag.py data


USAGE
-----

Start the chat interface by pointing the program at a folder of .docx files:

  python rag.py <path/to/folder>

Example:

  python rag.py data

On first run the system will:
  1. Download the embedding model (~90 MB, one time only)
  2. Extract and chunk all .docx files in the folder
  3. Embed and store all chunks in ChromaDB
  4. Open the interactive chat prompt

Subsequent runs load the existing index instantly.

Chat commands:

  You: <your question>   ask anything about the documents
  $quit                  exit the program

Example session:

  You: What are the main themes in the document?
  Bot: The document explores ...

  You: Who is the author?
  Bot: The author is ...

  You: $quit
  Bye.


INDEX MANAGEMENT
----------------

The vector index is stored in ./chroma_db/. It persists between runs.

To rebuild the index (e.g. after adding or removing documents):

  macOS/Linux:   rm -rf chroma_db/
  Windows:       rmdir /s /q chroma_db

Then run the program again to re-index.


CONFIGURATION
-------------

All tunable parameters are at the top of rag.py:

  Parameter          Default    Description
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  LLM_MODEL          gpt-oss:120b-cloud   Ollama Cloud model name
  EMBED_MODEL        all-MiniLM-L6-v2     Local ONNX embedding model
  CHROMA_DIR         ./chroma_db          Vector store directory
  CHUNK_SIZE         500                  Words per chunk
  CHUNK_OVERLAP      50                   Overlapping words between chunks
  TOP_K              5                    Chunks retrieved per query


SUPPORTED FILE FORMATS
----------------------

  .docx   Microsoft Word documents

Additional formats (PDF, .txt, etc.) can be added by extending the
load_and_index() function in rag.py.


HOW IT WORKS — DETAILED LOGIC
-----------------------------

The system operates in two distinct phases: an indexing phase (run once per
document set) and a query phase (run on every question). Understanding both
phases explains why the system is fast, accurate, and safe.


  PHASE 1 — INDEXING  (load_and_index)
  ─────────────────────────────────────

  Step 1: Startup check

    When you run `python rag.py data`, the program first checks whether a
    ChromaDB collection named after the folder already exists on disk inside
    ./chroma_db/. If it does, the entire indexing phase is skipped and the
    existing collection is loaded directly into memory. This is why subsequent
    runs start instantly.

    If no index exists, the full pipeline below runs.

  Step 2: Document parsing  (python-docx)

    Every .docx file in the folder is opened with python-docx, which reads
    the internal XML structure of the Word document. Only paragraph-level text
    is extracted — tables, headers, and footers are not currently included.
    All extracted text is lowercased to normalize the vocabulary before
    embedding, which improves matching consistency.

  Step 3: Text chunking  (split_text)

    Raw document text cannot be embedded as a whole — embedding models have a
    fixed token limit and long texts lose semantic precision. The text is
    therefore split into overlapping word-based windows:

      - CHUNK_SIZE   = 500 words  per chunk
      - CHUNK_OVERLAP = 50 words  shared between consecutive chunks

    The overlap is critical. Without it, a sentence that falls at the boundary
    between two chunks would be split in half. With 50 words of overlap, the
    context around every boundary exists in at least one complete chunk.

    Example with size=5, overlap=2 on "A B C D E F G H":

      chunk 0:  A B C D E
      chunk 1:  D E F G H
      chunk 2:  G H
      (step = 5 - 2 = 3 words forward each time)

    Each chunk is stored alongside metadata recording which source file it
    came from, so answers can later be attributed to a specific document.

  Step 4: Embedding  (all-MiniLM-L6-v2 via ONNX)

    Each text chunk is passed through the all-MiniLM-L6-v2 embedding model,
    which converts it into a 384-dimensional dense vector. This vector is a
    numerical "fingerprint" of the chunk's meaning — chunks with similar
    meaning have vectors that are close together in 384-dimensional space.

    The model runs entirely locally using ONNX Runtime. No text is sent
    anywhere during this step. On first use the model weights (~90 MB) are
    downloaded once from HuggingFace and cached locally.

    The same model is later used to embed the user's question, ensuring that
    the question and the documents share the same vector space and can be
    compared meaningfully.

  Step 5: Storing in ChromaDB

    ChromaDB is a vector database. It stores each chunk as a triplet:

      (id, vector, metadata)

      id        unique string like "doc_0", "doc_1", ...
      vector    384-float array produced by the embedding model
      metadata  {"source": "filename.docx"}

    The vectors are written to disk in ./chroma_db/ using a persistent client.
    Internally ChromaDB uses a HNSW index (Hierarchical Navigable Small World
    graph), a data structure that allows approximate nearest-neighbor search
    in sub-linear time — i.e. finding the most similar vectors without
    scanning every stored vector one by one.

    Chunks are sent to ChromaDB in batches of 100 to avoid memory pressure
    with large document sets.


  PHASE 2 — QUERY  (ask)
  ───────────────────────

  Step 1: Question embedding

    When you type a question, it is passed through the same all-MiniLM-L6-v2
    model that was used during indexing. This produces a 384-dimensional
    query vector that represents the semantic meaning of your question.

    Because both documents and question were embedded by the same model, their
    vectors live in the same space. A question about "the author's childhood"
    will produce a vector close to chunks that discuss the author's early life,
    even if the exact words differ.

  Step 2: Vector similarity search  (ChromaDB)

    ChromaDB receives the query vector and searches the HNSW index for the
    TOP_K (default: 5) stored vectors that are geometrically closest to it.
    Closeness is measured by cosine similarity — the cosine of the angle
    between two vectors. A cosine similarity of 1.0 means identical meaning;
    0.0 means unrelated.

    The search returns the 5 most semantically relevant chunks along with
    their source file names. This is the retrieval step — the R in RAG.

  Step 3: Prompt construction

    The retrieved chunks are assembled into a single context block, separated
    by dividers and labelled with their source file:

      [document1.docx]
      ...chunk text...

      ---

      [document2.docx]
      ...chunk text...

    This context is inserted into a structured prompt template alongside the
    user's question. The prompt explicitly instructs the model to answer using
    ONLY the provided context, and to reply with "IRRELEVANT" if the context
    does not contain sufficient information. This constraint prevents the model
    from drawing on its own training data and fabricating answers.

  Step 4: LLM generation  (Ollama Cloud)

    The fully assembled prompt is sent to the Ollama Cloud API over HTTPS. The
    Bearer token from OLLAMA_API_KEY is attached as an Authorization header.
    The cloud model (gpt-oss:120b-cloud) reads the prompt and generates an
    answer grounded in the provided context.

    This is the generation step — the G in RAG. The model at this point is
    acting as a reader and summarizer, not as a knowledge base. The knowledge
    comes from the retrieved chunks; the model contributes language fluency
    and reasoning.

  Step 5: Response filtering

    If the model replies with the exact word "IRRELEVANT", the system surfaces
    a clean "[No relevant answer found]" message rather than exposing the raw
    model token. Any other response is returned directly to the terminal.


  DATA FLOW SUMMARY
  ─────────────────

  Indexing:

    .docx
      └─ python-docx extracts paragraphs
           └─ lowercased, joined into full text
                └─ split into overlapping 500-word chunks
                     └─ each chunk embedded → 384-dim vector  [LOCAL]
                          └─ (id, vector, metadata) written to ChromaDB  [LOCAL]

  Query:

    user question
      └─ embedded → 384-dim query vector  [LOCAL]
           └─ HNSW nearest-neighbor search in ChromaDB  [LOCAL]
                └─ top-5 chunks retrieved with source labels  [LOCAL]
                     └─ prompt assembled: context + question
                          └─ sent to Ollama Cloud API  [NETWORK]
                               └─ LLM generates answer
                                    └─ printed to terminal


  WHAT STAYS LOCAL vs. WHAT LEAVES THE MACHINE
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────

    Operation                          Local   Network
    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    Document parsing                     YES
    Text chunking                        YES
    Embedding (indexing)                 YES
    Vector storage (ChromaDB)            YES
    Embedding (query time)               YES
    Vector similarity search             YES
    LLM answer generation                        YES *

    * Only the retrieved context (up to 5 chunks) and the question text are
      transmitted. Raw document files never leave the machine.


NOTES
-----

  - The embedding model runs entirely locally. No document content is sent
    to any external service during indexing.
  - Only the retrieved context and your question are sent to Ollama Cloud
    for answer generation.
  - The system returns "No relevant context found" when no chunks meet the
    similarity threshold, rather than hallucinating an answer.
